 What is a Struct?
A struct is a collection of related fields (like a class data holder).

type User struct {
    id    int
    Name  string
    email string
}


- Creating Structs
Using field names (recommended)
u := User{
    id:   1,
    name: "Go",
}

Without field names (order matters ❌)
u := User{1, "Go", "go@mail.com"}

-**- Zero Value of Struct
var u User
All fields get zero values
Struct itself is NOT nil

-- Accessing Fields
fmt.Println(u.Name)
u.Name = "Golang"

u := &User{
    id: 1,
}
✔ Recommended for performance.

-- Passing Struct to Function
❌ Value copy
func update(u User) {
    u.Name = "Go"
}
✅ Pointer (original updated)
func update(u *User) {
    u.Name = "Go"
}

- Methods in Go
A method is a function attached to a type.
func (u User) greet() {
    fmt.Println("Hello", u.Name)
}

--- Value Receiver vs Pointer Receiver (VERY IMPORTANT)
Value Receiver
func (u User) updateName(name string) {
    u.Name = name
}
❌ Does NOT update original.

Pointer Receiver
func (u *User) updateName(name string) {
    u.Name = name
}
✔ Updates original.

- Use pointer receiver when:
    Modifying struct
    Struct is large
    Consistency

Method Call Shortcut (INTERVIEW TRAP)
u := User{Name: "Go"}
u.updateName("Lang")
✔ Go automatically takes address.

***** Embedded Structs (Composition)
type Address struct {
    City string
}

type User struct {
    Name string
    Address
}

u.City = "Delhi"
✔ No inheritance, composition over inheritance.

**** Struct Tags (VERY IMPORTANT)
type User struct {
    Name string `json:"name"`
    Age  int    `json:"age,omitempty"`
}

Used in:
  JSON
  DB
  Validation

*** Anonymous Struct
user := struct {
    Name string
    Age  int
}{
    "Go",
    10,
}
✔ Useful for short-lived data.

---- Struct Comparison
u1 == u2 // valid if all fields are comparable
❌ Not allowed if struct contains:
  map
  slice
  func

**** Struct with Slices & Maps
type User struct {
    Skills []string
    Meta   map[string]string
}
⚠️ Maps must be initialized.

Constructor Pattern (COMMON) *****

func NewUser(name string) *User {
    return &User{Name: name}
}
✔ Idiomatic Go.

-*---- Methods on Non-Struct Types
type MyInt int

func (m MyInt) double() int {
    return int(m * 2)
}
✔ Methods can be on any type (except built-in).

/*/*/*/*/*/*/   Exported vs Unexported Fields
type User struct {
    Name string // exported
    age  int    // private
}
✔ Capital letter → exported.

- Struct
A struct is a composite data type that groups related fields together.

- Method
A method is a function associated with a receiver type.

- Pointer Receiver
Pointer receivers allow methods to modify the original struct and avoid copying.































